# SVC, NuSVC and LinearSVC are classes capable of performing multi-class classification on a dataset.

# Nearest Neighbors Classification

scikit-learn implements two different nearest neighbors classifiers: KNeighborsClassifier implements learn- ing based on the
ğ‘˜ nearest neighbors of each query point, where ğ‘˜ is an integer value specified by the user. RadiusNeighborsClassifier implements
learning based on the number of neighbors within a fixed radius ğ‘Ÿ of each training point, where ğ‘Ÿ is a floating-point value 
specified by the user.


### Gaussian Processes

Gaussian Processes (GP) are a generic supervised learning method designed to solve regression and probabilistic classification
problems.
The advantages of Gaussian processes are:
â€¢ The prediction interpolates the observations (at least for regular kernels).
â€¢ The prediction is probabilistic (Gaussian) so that one can compute empirical confidence intervals and decide based on those 
  if one should refit (online fitting, adaptive fitting) the prediction in some region of interest.
â€¢ Versatile: different kernels can be specified. Common kernels are provided, but it is also possible to specify custom kernels.

The disadvantages of Gaussian processes include:
â€¢ They are not sparse, i.e., they use the whole samples/features information to perform the prediction.
â€¢ They lose efficiency in high dimensional spaces â€“ namely when the number of features exceeds a few dozens.


The GaussianProcessClassifier implements Gaussian processes (GP) for classification purposes, more specifically for probabilistic
classification, where test predictions take the form of class probabilities


## Kernels for Gaussian Processes

Kernels (also called â€œcovariance functionsâ€ in the context of GPs) are a crucial ingredient of GPs which determine the shape of 
prior and posterior of the GP. They encode the assumptions on the function being learned by defining the â€œsimilarityâ€ of two 
datapoints combined with the assumption that similar datapoints should have similar target values.



## Naive Bayes

Naive Bayes methods are a set of supervised learning algorithms based on applying Bayesâ€™ theorem with the â€œnaiveâ€ assumption
of conditional independence between every pair of features given the value of the class variable. Bayesâ€™ theorem states the 
following relationship, given class variable ğ‘¦ and dependent feature vector ğ‘¥1 through ğ‘¥ğ‘›, :

                                        ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¦ | ğ‘¥1,...,ğ‘¥ğ‘›) = ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¦)ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¥1,...ğ‘¥ğ‘› | ğ‘¦) ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¥1,...,ğ‘¥ğ‘›)
                                        
Using the naive conditional independence assumption that
ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¥ğ‘–|ğ‘¦,ğ‘¥1,...,ğ‘¥ğ‘–âˆ’1,ğ‘¥ğ‘–+1,...,ğ‘¥ğ‘›) = ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¥ğ‘–|ğ‘¦), for all ğ‘–, this relationship is simplified to

                                        ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¦ | ğ‘¥1,...,ğ‘¥ğ‘›) = ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¦)âˆï¸€ğ‘›ğ‘–=1 ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¥ğ‘– | ğ‘¦) ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¥1,...,ğ‘¥ğ‘›)
                                        
Since ğ‘ƒ (ğ‘¥1 , . . . , ğ‘¥ğ‘› ) is constant given the input, we can use the following classification rule:

                                                ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¦ | ğ‘¥1,...,ğ‘¥ğ‘›) âˆ ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¦)âˆï¸ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¥ğ‘– | ğ‘¦)
                                                
                                                     ğ‘¦Ë†=argmax ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¦)âˆï¸ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¥ğ‘– |ğ‘¦)
                                                 
and we can use Maximum A Posteriori (MAP) estimation to estimate ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¦) and ğ‘ƒ(ğ‘¥ğ‘– | ğ‘¦); the former is then the
relative frequency of class ğ‘¦ in the training set.   

## Decision Trees

Decision Trees (DTs) are a non-parametric supervised learning method used for classification and regression. The goal is to 
create a model that predicts the value of a target variable by learning simple decision rules inferred from the data features.
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
  
      
